SIMPLE: ford
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ford
<hw>Ford</hw> <pr>(f⟦omac⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>ford</ets>; akin to G. <ets>furt</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fj⟦oum⟧r⟦edh⟧r</ets> bay, and to E. <ets>fare</ets>. ⟦root⟧78. See
<er>Fare</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Frith</er> arm of the
sea.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place in a river, or other water, where
it may be passed by man or beast on foot, by wading.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He swam the Esk river where <qex>ford</qex> there was none.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stream; a current.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With water of the <qex>ford</qex>⟦br⟧
Or of the clouds.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Permit my ghost to pass the Stygian <qex>ford</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ford</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ford
<hw>Ford</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Forded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fording</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To pass or cross, as a river or
other water, by wading; to wade through.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His last section, which is no deep one, remains only to be
<qex>forted</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fordable</ent>⟦br⟧
